{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c63a5f44-ea9e-4126-b987-3f036b76aaaf","content":"The most likely issue is that the **.NET Android SDK doesn't properly detect Adoptium Temurin's version string** during the build, even though `java -version` works fine in your terminal.\n\n**Recommended fix** — use the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the MAUI workload:\n\n```bash\n# Reinstall/repair the workload (includes Microsoft OpenJDK 17)\ndotnet workload install maui\n\n# Then remove or unset JAVA_HOME so the build uses the bundled JDK\nunset JAVA_HOME\n```\n\n**Alternative** — explicitly tell MSBuild to use your Temurin JDK by adding this to your `.csproj` or `Directory.Build.props`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Why this happens:** The .NET Android SDK ships its own JDK and uses specific version-detection logic. Third-party distributions (like Temurin) sometimes have version strings that don't match the expected regex, causing \"Java SDK not found\" or \"version too low\" errors even when the correct version is installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ba3113a-190f-488b-91e7-63fc415c5b58","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on macOS with a .NET MAUI Android build failing with a Java-related error. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed and JAVA_HOME points to it.\n\nThe common issue here is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK requires a specific JDK version. Let me think about what's likely wrong:\n\n1. .NET MAUI (especially newer versions like .NET 8+) requires JDK 17, which they have.\n2. However, a very common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is the **JAVA_HOME path**. \n\nOn macOS, Adoptium installs to a specific directory structure, but the path often gets misconfigured. The .NET Android SDK has its own JDK detection logic that checks the `JavaSdkDirectory`